    <thetext>The class

@NonNullByDefault
public class FullyQualifiedNullable {
	java.lang.@Nullable String text;
}

gives a compile error on &apos;text&apos;: &quot;The @NonNull field text may not have been initialized&quot;

Maybe I&apos;m wrong, but I think this is the correct way to annotate a fully qualified type. When removing &quot;java.lang.&quot;, the compiler no longer gives the error.</thetext>
  </long_desc><long_desc isprivate="0" >
    <commentid>2475286</commentid>
    <comment_count>1</comment_count>
    <who name="Stephan Herrmann">stephan.herrmann</who>
    <bug_when>2014-11-02 09:29:45 -0500</bug_when>
    <thetext>Thanks for the report. Yep, you&apos;re right about the syntax.

We are simply looking in the wrong place when applying @NNBD on the field (type annotations don&apos;t set the corresponding bit on the field, but only on its type). As a result the @NNBD overrides the explicit @Nullable.

Hudson will look into this, see https://git.eclipse.org/r/#/c/35777/</thetext>
  </long_desc><long_desc isprivate="0" >
